column7: Reserve Your Spot: Penn Campus Tours
column9:
Register today!

APPLY <https://www.gse.upenn.edu/admissions/application-requirements-deadlines?utm_campaign=inq_aw_all_2024&utm_content=tour&utm_medium=email&utm_source=drip>


JOIN US FOR A TOUR


                                      Register today!                                    




Go on a campus tour with a current Penn GSE student.
                                                                           

 Discover Penn's vibrant urban campus and explore Penn GSE's newly renovated facilities during a 45-minute guided walking tour. Join us in West Philadelphia for a closer look, with limited spots available on each tour.                                    




Tour Schedule
                                                                           

                                      Campus tours are available every Monday, Wednesday, and Friday at 11:00 a.m. (ET), excluding holidays. Advanced registration is required.                                    


Register <https://apply.gse.upenn.edu/portal/campus_tours?_gl=1*2t4vrm*_gcl_aw*R0NMLjE3MjE0MTQzMzQuQ2p3S0NBanduZWkwQmhCLUVpd0FBMnh1QnBTV1lNcWR5dm1uSVpxcjZsS3pueV81bXBBY3dPM1g3aGw4XzhKaHYyRWV5RUhMR0tJZlJob0NaTXdRQXZEX0J3RQ..*_gcl_au*MTk5NzY3Njc0OS4xNzE4NjMyOTI2LjEyNzU3NTY1MzMuMTcyMjQzNTc4NC4xNzIyNDM1Nzg0*_ga*MTQwMTcwNjA1Mi4xNzIxODQ0MjM4*_ga_10FWQ5NDJP*MTcyNDM1MDUzOC44NS4xLjE3MjQzNTA4NDAuNTMuMC4w&utm_campaign=inq_aw_all_2024&utm_content=tour&utm_medium=email&utm_source=drip>



                                      To attend your event on campus, we require all visitors to bring valid IDs, which will be verified upon entrance to our building.                                     




                                      Highlights of Campus                                    





                                      Penn GSE is located at 3700 Walnut Street in the heart of Penn's campus. Our recent renovation and addition have given us a stunning facility that provides incredible spaces for learning and connection.                                    


Locust Walk


                                      You can also access Penn GSE from Penn's famed Locust Walk, which runs through campus and features beautiful trees and iconic buildings.                                    


Can't get to campus?


                                      Join us for a Friday Virtual Chat to learn more about the campus and student life.                                    


Virtual Chat Schedule <https://apply.gse.upenn.edu/portal/friday_chats?_gl=1*o6993t*_gcl_aw*R0NMLjE3MjE0MTQzMzQuQ2p3S0NBanduZWkwQmhCLUVpd0FBMnh1QnBTV1lNcWR5dm1uSVpxcjZsS3pueV81bXBBY3dPM1g3aGw4XzhKaHYyRWV5RUhMR0tJZlJob0NaTXdRQXZEX0J3RQ..*_gcl_au*MTk5NzY3Njc0OS4xNzE4NjMyOTI2Ljg2OTIzODU5NC4xNzI0MzU2ODE4LjE3MjQzNTY5MjU.*_ga*MTQwMTcwNjA1Mi4xNzIxODQ0MjM4*_ga_10FWQ5NDJP*MTcyNDQyMTMyMi44Ny4wLjE3MjQ0MjEzMjkuNTMuMC4w&utm_campaign=inq_aw_all_2024&utm_content=tour&utm_medium=email&utm_source=drip>

Hey Candace,

Ever noticed how, as the week winds down, it’s easy to start
thinking about the weekend and put off tying up loose ends?

But here’s the thing: not wrapping up this week properly can make
next week feel like a scramble before it even begins.

To avoid that chaotic Monday morning feeling, I want to share one
of the most powerful tools I’ve found for staying on track: the
Weekly Review.

A Weekly Review is more than just a quick recap; it’s your chance
to zoom out, connect the dots of the past seven days, and see
where things are trending. It’s a time to catch your breath,
celebrate your wins, and make sure you’re setting yourself up for
success in the week ahead.

I sometimes even use my newsletter LifeNotes as a type of weekly
review and public journal for what I’ve got up to that week (if
that sounds interesting you can sign up here (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/e5uoz0xvqmu7hllpv2wa8h8r5g222tl/kkhmh2ul7vld3dak/aHR0cHM6Ly9hbGlhYmRhYWwuY29tL25ld3NsZXR0ZXIv
)).

By taking the time to review our week, we’re not only
acknowledging what worked well but also identifying what didn’t.
And that’s where real growth happens.

🗓️ My Weekly Review Routine
---------------------------

I discovered the concept of weekly review in David Allen’s book
*Getting Things Done (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/e5uoz0xvqmu7hllpv2wa8h8r5g222tl/25h2h9u25w2vegu8/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYW1hem9uLmNvbS9HZXR0aW5nLVRoaW5ncy1Eb25lLVN0cmVzcy1GcmVlLVByb2R1Y3Rpdml0eS9kcC8wMTQyMDAwMjgw
)* way back in 2018. I didn’t follow through at first, but now,
it’s become a key part of my routine.

Here’s my simple method:

* Set a Specific Time: I usually do this on Sunday evening, but
you can choose any time that works for you. The key is to be
consistent.
* Review Your Week: Compare your weekly goals or plan to what
actually happened. Did you hit the targets you set? Which areas
need improvement?
* Ask Yourself Key Questions:-* What gave me energy this week?
How can I make more time for those things?
* What drained my energy this week? How can I reduce time spent
on those things?
* What was my biggest win of the week?
* What was my biggest struggle of the week?
* Did my actions align with my long-term goals?

* Plan the Next Week: This is the ideal moment to lay out your
goals for the next seven days.

That’s it. It’s simple, doesn’t take too long, and gives me a
birds-eye view of my whole week. It lets me remember what the
most important parts of the week were, and lets me open any new
loops that I need to or close existing ones.

Every time I do this, I get to the end and think, “damn, I’m
really glad I did this”.

--------------------------------------------------------------
🎊 Connect the Dots: From Weekly Review to 12-Month Celebration
--------------------------------------------------------------

Now, here’s how the Weekly Review ties into something bigger:
your 12-Month Celebration.

This is one of my favourite strategies for long-term planning.

It’s simple: imagine it’s twelve months from now, and you’re
having dinner with your best friend, celebrating all the progress
you’ve made over the past year.

What would you want to tell them about your achievements?

For example:

* Work: I launched a couple of new products (Productivity Lab &
LifeOS) that help people do more of what matters to them.
* Health: I found a workout routine that I actually enjoy and
managed to stick with it consistently.
* Relationships: Plan 2 trips abroad with friends.

Each of these achievements would have been the result of dozens
of small actions taken week by week, starting with something as
simple as a Weekly Review. By regularly reflecting and planning,
you’re setting the stage for that 12-month celebration.

So, ask yourself: “If I want to make that celebration a reality,
what do I need to do over the next year to get there? What’s the
first action step I can take next week?”

Whether it’s sticking to a writing routine, planning YouTube
videos, or staying consistent with workouts, the actions you plan
today will shape the story you tell a year from now.

-------------------------------------
📢 Challenge: Share Your Weekly Review
-------------------------------------

Experiment with the Weekly Review to wrap up your week and plan
for the one ahead:

* Take 15-30 minutes to do a Weekly Review this Sunday (or
whenever suits you) and use the steps I’ve mentioned as a guide.
* Think about how this week’s actions connect to your long-term
goals and your 12-month celebration.
* When you’re done, share your Weekly Review with me or on your
socials to keep you accountable. I’d love to see how you’re
setting yourself up for success.

By the way, if you found this exercise helpful, Productivity Lab
actually runs live online Weekly Review sessions every week to
hold you accountable to your goals.

In addition to the Weekly Reviews, you’ll also have access to
live online co-working sessions, accountability pods, monthly
expert workshops from guest speakers, access to my LifeOS course,
and much, much more.

Productivity Lab and LifeOS both reopen on Monday 17th February
at 4PM GMT, so if you’re interested in finding more about this
I'll be sending you a couple of short emails to let you know
about that before the launch in just three days.

And, there we go, that’s a wrap on this 5-day Productivity
Challenge. All that’s left to say is congratulations 🎉

I hope you’ve found these strategies and exercises helpful and
that they’ve brought a bit more joy, fun and effectiveness to
your daily routine.

Ali xx

​

References:

* Czyżowska, N., & Gurba, E. (2021). Does Reflection on Everyday
Events Enhance Meaning in Life and Well-Being among Emerging
Adults? Self-Efficacy as Mediator between Meaning in Life and
Well-Being. International Journal of Environmental Research and
Public Health, 18(18): 9714.

Quick question:

If you’re not taking action to become a Premium Ghostwriter right
now, when do you plan to start?

Because if you want to build a lucrative ghostwriting side hustle
in 2025, you need to start… today.

But one of the most common excuses I hear from people who WANT to
start ghostwriting but don’t is:

“I don’t have the time.”

But here’s a brutal truth:
--------------------------

I didn’t have the time either.

Most people don’t know this, but I was working full time at
BlackRock when I started my ghostwriting career. I didn’t have
much free time to work with so I spent early mornings and late
evenings writing and (begrudgingly) stared at charts and numbers
for my Wall Street job during the day.

Which is why I like to say…

For the things you care about, you don’t find the time.

You MAKE the time.

And if I hadn’t made the time, I wouldn’t have made my first
$5,000 ghostwriting on the internet:

​

If you want to start ghostwriting, then “I don’t have the time”
can’t be an excuse.
-----------------------------------------------------------------

It’s easy to fall into the trap of “once XYZ happens… then I’ll
start writing.”

* “Once I feel ready…”
* “Once work slows down…”
* “Once I build up my confidence…”
* “Once I get settled in my new role…”

But the truth is, these “Onces” never go away.

It will never be the “perfect time” to start something. And if
you sit around waiting for it, you’ll look back years later with
regret.

So, if this sounds like the story going on in your head, I have a
question for you.

Do you have 30 minutes per day?
-------------------------------

Just so you know, we designed the Premium Ghostwriting Academy
for people who don’t have much time.

People who don’t have hours and hours of “spare time” and need to
learn how to create massive results in their life in compressed
periods of time—30 minutes here, 15 minutes there.

The time investment for PGA is approximately 30 minutes per day,
with plenty of resources, videos, and Slack community for you to
use at your leisure.

Plus, you get 1-to-1 mentorship from your own dedicated Success
Coach to keep you accountable and on track through the program.

And if you can’t make all (or any) of the live sessions, don’t
worry. We provide recordings for you to watch when is most
convenient for you, and we also give you plenty of written
content for you to skim and apply to your own ghostwriting
business in real time.

The entire program is organized in a way that caters to every
learning style, with a strong emphasis on taking action.

After all, that’s where all the growth is (not in consuming hours
and hours of videos that help you learn “in theory” but don’t
actually move you forward).

So, as the year comes to a close and you think about the year
ahead, ask yourself:

If not in 2025, then when?

column7: Thank you for applying to HelloFresh!
column9:
Hi Candace,

Thanks for applying to HelloFresh! There are a ton of great companies out there, so we appreciate your interest in joining our team.

You put time and effort into your application, so we'll make sure we give it the attention it deserves. While we’re not able to reach out to every applicant, we will contact you if your skills and experience are a strong match for the role.

HelloFresh participates in the Work Opportunity Tax Credit program, which may assist members of targeted groups in securing employment. We encourage you to help us make this program a success by clicking the link below and answering the questions to the best of your ability. Your responses to the questions are completely voluntary and will be confidential to this company's management and third-party service providers, federal, state and local agencies, and other third parties as necessary to determine eligibility. You will be given a 6 digit confirmation code upon completion of the survey. Please make note of your code, as it may be requested if hired. The information you give will be used to determine the company's eligibility for these programs and will in no way negatively impact any hiring, retention or promotion decisions.

HelloFresh's Work Opportunity Tax Credit Program ( https://tcs.adp.com/txcs-ui/screening/?cc=hellofresh )

In the meantime, if you'd like to keep up to date with the latest HelloFresh news and opportunities, you can join our talent community ( https://careers.hellofresh.com/global/en/jointalentcommunity?applyType=JTC )!

If all that job searching is making you hungry, here's some of our delicious recipes from HelloFresh ( https://www.hellofresh.com/ ).

Best wishes,

Your HelloFresh Recruiting Team

Hey Candace,

Just a little note as we head into the weekend.

I wanted to quickly talk about the importance of accountability
and community in the creator space, especially as it relates to
starting on YouTube.

The thing is, more and more people are joining the platform each
year, new creators are emerging, new channels are being
created…it feels like the space is expanding rapidly.

And yet, growing a channel as a solo creator can be incredibly
lonely.

Back in 2017 when I started, I certainly didn’t have anyone to
turn to get feedback on my videos or get advice about thumbnails
or titles.

Even now, it’s probably unlikely that you can turn to your
friends or family to talk about CTR or AVD or get their feedback
on a particular video idea or title suggestion 😅

And whether you’re just starting out, or you’ve got thousands of
subscribers, trying to do YouTube alone makes the journey even
harder.

In fact, one of the things that gets mentioned repeatedly by
students who’ve had success going through the Part-Time YouTuber
Academy (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/92u972n8rdtnh6l307za9hz5d6d33cw/6qhehoulwn5d4xu9/aHR0cHM6Ly9hbGlhYmRhYWwuY29tL3BhcnQtdGltZS15b3V0dWJlci1hY2FkZW15
), is that the community provided those spaces to connect with
like-minded individuals who ‘got it’ - people who resonated with
the struggles and could provide accountability in the early
stages.

And that’s so important not just for the advice that you receive
but for the motivation that it provides to keep creating content
consistently, which is key to success on YouTube.

If you join PTYA (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/92u972n8rdtnh6l307za9hz5d6d33cw/6qhehoulwn5d4xu9/aHR0cHM6Ly9hbGlhYmRhYWwuY29tL3BhcnQtdGltZS15b3V0dWJlci1hY2FkZW15
), you not only unlock access to those spaces but also get
invited to all the events that we run for students aimed at
providing expertise to accelerate your own learning and
progression.

For instance, next week we’ve actually organised five of these
events as part of our first Creator Week including sessions on
scripting, product creation, vlogging, growth strategies and
more.

And just as a reminder there’s now less than 36 hours before the
limited time offer on PTYA comes to an end.

You can still get 15% off (almost $150) until midnight (BST) on

By Melissa Kirsch
[https://nl.nytimes.com/f/newsletter/KQquO6WOYW0T0tXWVRMdQQ~~/AAAAARA~/RdAyJ0vAU6a9UuTDSOeH4jVm0bJZU_rNDseCrJREK3JlBf9IaH1mHRx91U52tX2MThk3W_LwnrLCZaZAQyB-TB2-r-TuYkFR8VXz54qsuc5w7tlFVjiNgetXL01_V_cp5KjZSr-tl8oL09L5hz02sFiG0tlGOS-1AfgeHpFrhM-aO3iERArlfDaomML4TX0nWVkxuj23NsSP7B5W09EmxwR3Pi8X2jLvZoiWvkj8sioeFT4U76Y8A8hj7SE8Q7Ovgt00w3qho2hrybWXJWd6rbjSxDuorg0H1QJdVqWAz4SyeqQybtoRWQb62r_STfirSS6VaV7YkkZ-I7KrMJUeAw~~]

A recent story in The Times, by Emily Laber-Warren, describes the ways we relate
to time
[https://nl.nytimes.com/f/newsletter/-9Le5VZnVJ75Xf20OAowkQ~~/AAAAARA~/4MO6SNoe_WFhv5YTinWe52eCqhnE8XYjJ7AcxGnDNLpzAlYJZsfe9_VT20QPnsM_x2O6bVsJFDa5h2oC0eHuK9Gymm-PmLP-AY0JI93D09R3Au3Eq-XRMOuiRtvkgcfIwNg-W0YaVJz9Foic3CkgdXl5beCWSvMufH8yvnk66k3LrPMG0O9EH414o_--sTdDcNuaUM0H9C5-G6RnZ3kbMyBA7rmBHLDDpy2forGa4U4YNX6_AKAGT72DeLW3O5752aVsawLM-rpHoMPOIicj-EGG6thoi6DHhLMmHo373sTzlqZtyItMztsmyiK6fwUh25FK4J6DGH5DtpU8srosrah2XtQH6ZdyyEjRLEp1zpn-lNJ7s59dSnzBPzRzAbmljG-MUN5rtJzrLZlGwHzI-g~~]
, dividing us into two groups. Monochronic people “tend to live by the clock and
are primed, at least during work hours, to prioritize obligations over
relationships.” Polychronic people, on the other hand, “tend to give primacy to
experiences and relationships that don’t always fit neatly into prearranged
schedules.” If you prefer to work on one thing at a time, emphasizing deadlines
and seeing interruptions as irritating, you’re monochronic. Those who are good
at multitasking, who comfortably allow shifts in their schedules if, for
example, a friend comes to town and wants to go for a hike — those people are
probably polychronic.

The article insists there are downsides with each time personality. Monochronic
people can be rigid, missing out on serendipity. Polychronic people can be
easily distracted and can have difficulty finishing what they start. But I found
myself thinking, as I often do when I read about socially scientific binaries —
Type A vs. Type B, maximizers vs. satisficers
[https://nl.nytimes.com/f/a/grmrNes_Qn2vZ6N0dkqO0A~~/AAAAARA~/nZT3S8shYgoyanrM1gXo7PrYuwCwa0behNKc9ZDy0pK6nK5ccwn-tMoQfVjsnIsrEW4OWxXZ7GTSh2g0Kd50ieU-QuJhdKMqNiSSwDLmNsvDADgtaVcOYiJ9LmrotRde6Gjz9Z__tITBYFzRN4_qMoea-qfJ9p2DIGQIvE2ByQimDeDW4-JHj5AuNhmx7QKJmohnio69MG7s4POyxh6yI2l_B_a-2MhoM6msQj5q2dxHURuGPBZ-WOPYVkVjJLtz-LtF7S3b3pi3ZLPOxgKOfaqWowSz2udlDYstVt0S2BkcHivvdXCGuJSE7EuJgby7t77LhA08qgtQeGRsSjSPgP9NoWgPKIAw-tMZOjiQZM0MsnzIup9fPGpx2eNcZGwhfnO3fhWkTTebybktWQUnXw~~] 
— that it’s secretly better to be the more laid-back type, that life is richer
and more fulfilling if you’re less rigid and don’t, say, view a deadline the way
a beast of burden does a plowman’s whip. Despite my efforts to be loose and
breezy with time, I’m pretty regimented. Calling myself “monochronic” allows me
to justify what I have always characterized as an undesirable uptightness. While
I want to be productive, I want so much more to prioritize relationships over
industry, to say “this can wait” when I’m fast at work and someone calls with
last-minute theater tickets.

We’re obsessed with our attention these days, how it’s been captured by our
screens, attenuated by too-busy schedules and the impossible pace of modern
life. Monotasking
[https://nl.nytimes.com/f/newsletter/7ldzeXSYYatu_XQYpSPtow~~/AAAAARA~/ibvfR_SOcQIFCNlMAz28g7Bg1DNMvC557Lmuj7AddnNkbGkVg1JuC-VtqERvJ7W6Y7NFazIxi7xbYSAyi8BikJOLAd1N6C-iPqYKWWg4gkVC57qBfGyDLHOZlaotXlXaM7bOMAPM36LTHpEMm7JShgq_6myMFSASH01FCM1mXgL_7SXBkuihaotubmzjH7EoL26fid8GewcA8KNDQuwq7Gt1gYRw5jYIli3jt82TAiUhM7jXWqdipnCREeA_z8KFcxzOysEKF2gZqs3bXTNQWUE78G1OQ011FpNTgRZhtY6tOBukJ9sJ242HlzKsnump8-Msvy_0bDUTOVBJya8SmNOy2D67n1LUNKsuFgHOciM~] 
is seen as an advantageous skill, deep work and flow states the antidotes to
cognitive fatigue. But as we try to marshal our attention, it seems possible we
will be tempted to overcorrect. My monochronic preference for uninterrupted
stretches of time in which to work — oh, the exquisite relief of turning on “Do
Not Disturb” on my laptop and knowing that it will also silence my phone, my
iPad, the text alerts and weather alerts and news alerts and calendar alerts! —
often keeps me from engaging with things that would bring me pleasure. I’ve
missed perfect 75-degree days because I need to finish chores before I relax. I
tell myself that nothing will feel as good as getting things done, but then I
think of the cliché about people on their deathbeds never saying they wish
they’d spent more time working.

There’s hope: Time personalities are preferences, not traits, so we can shift
them. The aim, as in all things, is balance, being nimble enough to shift from
one style to another as the situation prescribes. “Is your goal here
relationship building? Then go polychronic,” one expert in the article advised.
“If your goal is to complete a task, then we need to be monochronic for a window
of time and shut out all distractions.” While switching gears may feel
uncomfortable for those of us conditioned to do the thing until the thing is
done, this framing highlights the stakes. Completing the task feels good, but —
here comes the deathbed again — the accomplishment is hollow without some
flexibility, without letting in the possibility for surprise, serendipity and
delight.

🎸 Ethel Cain, “Willoughby Tucker, I’ll Always Love You” (Out now): On a
summer’s day about two years ago, standing in a field in West London, I fell in
love with the music of Ethel Cain, the southern gothic persona of the singer
Hayden Anhedönia. It happened during her performance of “A House in Nebraska
[https://nl.nytimes.com/f/a/Xs3kLQEccnV55Pb1nxIE2Q~~/AAAAARA~/L3_ZQDC6o7JzqfuYij1XqCMU1vnogdpn6KegyUJTvsNqQOldNwU3xURRXCf1g7g3uhiSscGDUvRb5FO3F2i042q8a3MjAcQxOpuNCGF_KnHX6FA9enN4-gWVz_OqNfsFdV06xQalIuJJgnKjzG_Sl9mIuueMw-UheGJon3GwxF3z3pa9IAoVLK8LX5DUMwcRI5OoXKSJ3H10X6wOP6hqfkU6StceAY4MMfLM-QcQIB_XTdq0NoiUjecnub40M6uFvnMPxrCNpfMCaQAbOne8V-RXGO8dUON24_Gj7B6FEfqYNn__0PcoQPDg0s9TpgvkVlrLQTLJfwYpeUexbfAbnw1P2tHqLuaaK9g1aTglaTT129AeVcQmI1Xk56f8r7d7]
,” a cinematic, nearly eight-minute track about regret and lost love. There was
more where that came from — much of the rest of her 2022 debut album,
“Preacher’s Daughter,” was just as rich and just as evocative. This new album is
supposed to be second in a trilogy of albums from Ethel’s perspective — I’m
looking forward to entering her cinematic universe once more.

column7: ⚡️ You're Invited to Productivity Spark 2025 (for FREE)
column9:
Hey Candace,

As we approach the end of the year, I’ve been thinking a lot about how we can make 2025 a year of real, meaningful progress.

If you’re anything like me, you’ve probably set ambitious goals before, only to watch them lose steam after a few weeks. It’s not because we lack motivation — it’s because we often don’t have the right plan to turn those goals into action.

That’s why I’m so excited to announce Productivity Spark 2025: a completely free, live, and virtual productivity summit happening the first weekend of January, designed to help you plan your most productive year yet and start taking immediate action on your biggest goals.

You can register by clicking this link:

👉 Join the FREE Productivity Summit
(https://djX7c204.eu1.hubspotlinks.com/Ctc/5H+113/djX7c204/VWcmhX46Ml33VHWQHz80Y8NjW3Z50n15pss1_MyCDms3pyd0W7lCdLW6lZ3pTW69x9xh3fQ4YVVL0c-G5QHDqvW9ffxH983bQmhW2xQ_PM3TR-xnW5ghfvD8MQtgnW1vww_x8J0xZGW9879vR2Y0CK9VTCJ_J59M7q0W7C9m3m7Gq-hxW52WMfz9kCnqXW1G2Nht5vRCsLW3rjVDf4LmZnLW3mkzrQ8-NVWRW1VzYNP99wqRtW1wVntL1JzgTqW2KSts32Z4WmyW73m-DR97TXCpW94TySJ1GTPhLW81MKwy4TRJK5W1NdryK7NM4fYW3wRyZs6Tr9ZVW3ZnKtR35M-rMW4dqYKW6X9JF9W1--Rpp99RV2Lf4GP6gn04 )

What to Expect:

This summit isn’t about cramming your schedule or overloading you with productivity hacks. Nor is it about passively listening to the same productivity advice you’ve heard a million times before.

At Productivity Spark 2025, we’re focusing on interactive, taught sessions designed to help you leave with something tangible. Whether it’s a roadmap for your goals, a clear action plan for your projects, or a new productivity system, you’ll walk away with more than just inspiration — you’ll leave with a real toolkit for success.

Here’s how we’re structuring the event to make it as actionable as possible:

- Core sessions from me where we’ll dive deep into planning strategies and productivity systems. These aren’t just lectures — they’re hands-on workshops where you’ll work on your own goals in real-time.
- Guest-led workshops from incredible speakers (details coming soon!) with a focus on practical exercises and frameworks you can immediately apply.
- Interactive activities to help you craft your 2025 roadmap, so you leave with a clear, actionable plan.
- VIP Bonus Workshops on AI Powered Productivity, that you can access after registration.

Everything is designed to help you take action. No fluff. No “one-size-fits-all” advice. Just practical tools and inspiration to set you up for success.

Why You Should Join:

The start of the year is when we’re most motivated to make changes, but without the right plan, that motivation can fizzle out fast.

Productivity Spark 2025 is here to give you the clarity, structure, and momentum you need to hit the ground running.

Whether you’re looking to:

- Start a side hustle
- Grow your YouTube channel
- Achieve work-life balance
- Or finally tackle that passion project you’ve been putting off

…this summit will set you up for success for the year ahead 🥳

Mark Your Calendar:

📅 When: Saturday 4 January 2025 - Sunday 5 January 2025

🖥️ Where: Online — join from anywhere in the world

If you’re interested in joining you can register down below where I’ll be sharing more details of the event, including the full lineup of speakers:

👉 Join the FREE Productivity Summit
(https://djX7c204.eu1.hubspotlinks.com/Ctc/5H+113/djX7c204/VWcmhX46Ml33VHWQHz80Y8NjW3Z50n15pss1_MyCDms3pyd0W7lCdLW6lZ3pTW69x9xh3fQ4YVVL0c-G5QHDqvW9ffxH983bQmhW2xQ_PM3TR-xnW5ghfvD8MQtgnW1vww_x8J0xZGW9879vR2Y0CK9VTCJ_J59M7q0W7C9m3m7Gq-hxW52WMfz9kCnqXW1G2Nht5vRCsLW3rjVDf4LmZnLW3mkzrQ8-NVWRW1VzYNP99wqRtW1wVntL1JzgTqW2KSts32Z4WmyW73m-DR97TXCpW94TySJ1GTPhLW81MKwy4TRJK5W1NdryK7NM4fYW3wRyZs6Tr9ZVW3ZnKtR35M-rMW4dqYKW6X9JF9W1--Rpp99RV2Lf4GP6gn04 )

I’m convinced ghostwriting is the single best way for anyone to
monetize their writing skills.

However, most people have *zero* idea how to actually get
started.

So, I recorded a video answering 8 of the biggest questions all
ghostwriters have:

* The most challenging part of writing for high-profile clients.
​

Hey Candace,

Hope you’ve had a good start to the week 🙌

My team have all just arrived in Hong Kong for our team offsite
and the energy of working together in-person just hits different,
especially when we’ve been fully remote for so long.

And working with other people is actually what I wanted to talk
about today when it comes to productivity.

Yesterday I explained how LifeOS (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/4zuk32p06mtehp9lp97uxh6gddv77s5/qvh8h8ud7p4236sg/aHR0cHM6Ly9hbGlhYmRhYWwuY29tL2xpZmVvcy8_dXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPXR1ZXNkYXlfMSZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9cG9zdF9ldmVudF9zZXF1ZW5jZQ==
) differs from other productivity systems by adapting to you
rather than forcing you to adapt to it.

But creating a system is step one.

Implementing that system is what turns resolutions into results
and ambition into action.

I can talk about frameworks to set your vision and offer you
systems for taking action but it still requires you to actually
take that step and implement things consistently to make
progress.

And doing that on your own isn’t easy.

There are some people who can maintain the discipline and
self-motivation to take consistent daily action but a lot of
people struggle, including me 😅

Ever since university where I’d organise co-working study
sessions, my personal productivity has always been supercharged
by working with other people.

That continued when I started my business where I’ve always found
it easier to move the needle on important projects when we come
together as a team - just like we’re doing this week in Hong
Kong.

And I know I’m not alone.

Accountability is a superpower that unlocks a level of
productivity you never knew existed.

And that’s why I created LifeOS Pro (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/4zuk32p06mtehp9lp97uxh6gddv77s5/qvh8h8ud7p4236sg/aHR0cHM6Ly9hbGlhYmRhYWwuY29tL2xpZmVvcy8_dXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPXR1ZXNkYXlfMSZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9cG9zdF9ldmVudF9zZXF1ZW5jZQ==
) - a 12 month membership programme that takes the philosophy,
systems and frameworks of LifeOS but supercharges them with a
level of support and accountability that makes the path to
progress that much easier.

Think about it:

* Why do people hire personal trainers when workout information
is free?
* Why do writers join writing groups when they already know how
to write?
* Why do entrepreneurs hire coaches when they already understand
business principles?

Because accountability transforms intentions into actions.

Welcome to Supabase, the Postgres development platform.

Supabase gives you all the backend features you need to build a product: Database, Authentication, Storage, Realtime API, Edge Functions, Serverless APIs, and more.

→ Create Your First Project: https://supabase.com/dashboard/new


🔒 Planning for scale? Here's what matters:

- Harden Your Data API: Replace the public schema with a custom schema so private tables are not exposed.
  https://supabase.com/docs/guides/database/hardening-data-api

- Implement Row Level Security: Enable RLS on tables and create policies that filter data per user with proper indexing.
  https://supabase.com/docs/guides/database/postgres/row-level-security

- Review our Production Readiness checklist: Enable SSL enforcement, network restrictions, custom SMTP, and PITR backups for scale.
  https://supabase.com/docs/guides/deployment/going-into-prod


Feel free to reach out if you have any questions or feedback.

Paul, CEO and Co-Founder @ Supabase
